text: To reduce the binary size. The first and most obvious step is to build a project in release mode. By default, Cargobuild uses debug mode, which optimizes for ease of debugging. text: With this change, the release binary is now 1.3 megabytes. Next, we'll tell cargo to optimize for binary size using the optimization level option. By default, cargo optimizes for runtime speed for release builds. To change this, we'll set op level to s, which tells cargo to optimize for binary size. Note that there are several optimization levels available, and the rust documentation recommends experimenting with different levels to find the right balance for your project. After changing the optimization level, the release binary is now 1.2 megabytes.

text: The next step we'll take is to enable link time optimization by setting LTO equal to true in cargo toml.

text: This instructs the linker to optimize at the link stage at the expense of longer linking time. After this change, the release binary is less than 1 mb in size. We've made a lot of progress.
